        "template--21646019330355__f25aeaa3-9890-4cc8-a120-e2615fe6b616-text-1": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<h2><strong>Benefits:</strong></h2><ul><li><strong>6-Bolt:</strong> Offers broader rotor availability and might be simpler for DIY maintenance.</li><li><strong>Centerlock:</strong> Generally quicker to install and remove, potentially lighter due to fewer parts, and offers a cleaner appearance.</li></ul><p>The choice between the two often comes down to personal preference, compatibility with other bike components, and the ease of use during installation and maintenance. Some hub and brake manufacturers offer adapters to allow the use of different types of rotors on their hubs.The two main disc brake rotor interfaces are the 6-bolt and the centerlock designs. Here are their differences and benefits:</p><p></p><p></p><h3></h3><p></p>"
